    <!-- 1. Bond Pricing -->
    <h3>Bond pricing</h3>
    <p>A bond pays periodic coupons C and returns face value F at maturity. Its price is the sum of discounted cash flows: P = &sum; C/(1+y)<sup>t</sup> + F/(1+y)<sup>n</sup>. This is just TVM applied to a fixed schedule.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`(define (range a b) (if (> a b) '() (cons a (range (+ a 1) b))))

; Bond price = PV of coupons + PV of face value
(define (bond-price coupon face-value yield n)
  (let ((pv-coupons
         (apply + (map (lambda (t)
                         (/ coupon (expt (+ 1 yield) t)))
                       (range 1 n))))
        (pv-face (/ face-value (expt (+ 1 yield) n))))
    (+ pv-coupons pv-face)))

; 10-year bond, $1000 face, 5% coupon, 5% yield = par
(display "At par (5% coupon, 5% yield): $")
(display (round (bond-price 50 1000 0.05 10)))
(newline)

; Same bond, yield rises to 6% -> price falls
(display "Yield 6%: $")
(display (round (bond-price 50 1000 0.06 10)))
(newline)

; Yield drops to 4% -> price rises
(display "Yield 4%: $")
(display (round (bond-price 50 1000 0.04 10)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Bond pricing
def bond_price(coupon, face, y, n):
    pv_coupons = sum(coupon / (1 + y) ** t for t in range(1, n + 1))
    pv_face = face / (1 + y) ** n
    return pv_coupons + pv_face

# 10-year, $1000 face, 5% coupon
print(f"At par (5% coupon, 5% yield): \${bond_price(50, 1000, 0.05, 10):.2f}")
print(f"Yield 6%: \${bond_price(50, 1000, 0.06, 10):.2f}")
print(f"Yield 4%: \${bond_price(50, 1000, 0.04, 10):.2f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Yield to Maturity -->
    <h3>Yield to maturity</h3>
    <p><strong>Yield to maturity</strong> (YTM) is the single discount rate that makes the bond's price equal the PV of its cash flows. It is the bond's internal rate of return if held to maturity. Finding YTM requires solving P = &sum; C/(1+y)<sup>t</sup> + F/(1+y)<sup>n</sup> for y &mdash; no closed form, so we use bisection.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`(define (range a b) (if (> a b) '() (cons a (range (+ a 1) b))))

; Yield to maturity via bisection
(define (bond-price c f y n)
  (+ (apply + (map (lambda (t) (/ c (expt (+ 1 y) t)))
                   (range 1 n)))
     (/ f (expt (+ 1 y) n))))

(define (find-ytm price c f n)
  (let loop ((lo 0.001) (hi 0.5) (iter 0))
    (let* ((mid (/ (+ lo hi) 2))
           (p (bond-price c f mid n)))
      (if (or (> iter 100) (< (abs (- p price)) 0.01))
          mid
          (if (> p price)
              (loop mid hi (+ iter 1))
              (loop lo mid (+ iter 1)))))))

; Bond trading at $925, $1000 face, 5% coupon, 10 years
(define ytm (find-ytm 925 50 1000 10))
(display "YTM for bond at $925: ")
(display (round (* ytm 10000)))
(display " bps (")
(display (* (round (* ytm 10000)) 0.01))
(display "%)")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Yield to maturity via bisection
def bond_price(c, f, y, n):
    return sum(c / (1 + y) ** t for t in range(1, n + 1)) + f / (1 + y) ** n

def find_ytm(price, c, f, n, tol=0.0001):
    lo, hi = 0.001, 0.5
    for _ in range(200):
        mid = (lo + hi) / 2
        p = bond_price(c, f, mid, n)
        if abs(p - price) < tol:
            return mid
        if p > price:
            lo = mid
        else:
            hi = mid
    return mid

ytm = find_ytm(925, 50, 1000, 10)
print(f"YTM for bond at $925: {ytm:.4f} ({ytm*100:.2f}%)")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 3. Duration -->
    <h3>Duration and convexity</h3>
    <p><strong>Macaulay duration</strong> is the weighted-average time to receive cash flows, weighted by present value. It measures interest rate sensitivity: a bond with duration D loses roughly D% in price for a 1% rise in yield. <strong>Convexity</strong> captures the curvature &mdash; the error in the linear duration approximation.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`(define (range a b) (if (> a b) '() (cons a (range (+ a 1) b))))

; Macaulay duration = sum(t * PV(CF_t)) / Price
(define (bond-price c f y n)
  (+ (apply + (map (lambda (t) (/ c (expt (+ 1 y) t)))
                   (range 1 n)))
     (/ f (expt (+ 1 y) n))))

(define (macaulay-duration c f y n)
  (let* ((price (bond-price c f y n))
         (weighted-sum
          (+ (apply + (map (lambda (t)
                             (* t (/ c (expt (+ 1 y) t))))
                           (range 1 n)))
             (* n (/ f (expt (+ 1 y) n))))))
    (/ weighted-sum price)))

; Modified duration = Macaulay / (1+y)
(define (modified-duration c f y n)
  (/ (macaulay-duration c f y n) (+ 1 y)))

; 10-year, 5% coupon, 6% yield
(define dur (macaulay-duration 50 1000 0.06 10))
(define mod-dur (modified-duration 50 1000 0.06 10))

(display "Macaulay duration: ") (display (/ (round (* dur 100)) 100)) (display " years") (newline)
(display "Modified duration: ") (display (/ (round (* mod-dur 100)) 100))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Duration
def bond_price(c, f, y, n):
    return sum(c / (1 + y) ** t for t in range(1, n + 1)) + f / (1 + y) ** n

def macaulay_duration(c, f, y, n):
    price = bond_price(c, f, y, n)
    weighted = sum(t * c / (1 + y) ** t for t in range(1, n + 1))
    weighted += n * f / (1 + y) ** n
    return weighted / price

def modified_duration(c, f, y, n):
    return macaulay_duration(c, f, y, n) / (1 + y)

dur = macaulay_duration(50, 1000, 0.06, 10)
mod = modified_duration(50, 1000, 0.06, 10)
print(f"Macaulay duration: {dur:.2f} years")
print(f"Modified duration: {mod:.2f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Yield Curve -->
    <h3>Yield curve shapes</h3>
    <p>The <strong>yield curve</strong> plots yield against maturity. A normal curve slopes up: longer bonds demand higher yields for bearing more risk. An inverted curve (short rates above long rates) historically signals recession. A flat curve means the market sees no term premium.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Spot rates for different maturities
; Normal yield curve: rates increase with maturity
(define normal-curve
  (list (cons 1 0.03) (cons 2 0.035) (cons 5 0.04)
        (cons 10 0.045) (cons 30 0.05)))

; Price a zero-coupon bond using spot rate
(define (zero-price face spot n)
  (/ face (expt (+ 1 spot) n)))

(display "--- Normal yield curve ---") (newline)
(for-each (lambda (point)
            (let ((mat (car point)) (rate (cdr point)))
              (display mat) (display "yr spot: ")
              (display (* 100 rate)) (display "%, ")
              (display "$1000 zero = $")
              (display (round (zero-price 1000 rate mat)))
              (newline)))
          normal-curve)

; Forward rate between year 1 and year 2
; (1+s2)^2 = (1+s1)(1+f_{1,2})
(define s1 0.03)
(define s2 0.035)
(define f12 (- (/ (expt (+ 1 s2) 2) (+ 1 s1)) 1))
(newline)
(display "1yr forward rate (yr1->yr2): ")
(display (/ (round (* f12 10000)) 100))
(display "%")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Yield curve and forward rates
curve = [(1, 0.03), (2, 0.035), (5, 0.04), (10, 0.045), (30, 0.05)]

def zero_price(face, spot, n):
    return face / (1 + spot) ** n

print("--- Normal yield curve ---")
for mat, rate in curve:
    p = zero_price(1000, rate, mat)
    print(f"{mat}yr spot: {rate*100}%, $1000 zero = \${p:.2f}")

# Forward rate from year 1 to year 2
s1, s2 = 0.03, 0.035
f12 = (1 + s2)**2 / (1 + s1) - 1
print(f"\\n1yr forward rate (yr1->yr2): {f12*100:.2f}%")
`} />
